#Spatial join KSI to MSOA
```{r}
library(sf)
library(dplyr)
library(purrr)
library(here)

msoa_dir <- here("DATA", "msoa_2021", "LB_MSOA2021_shp", "msoa2021")

msoa_files <- list.files(msoa_dir, pattern = "\\.shp$", full.names = TRUE)

length(msoa_files)      # 
head(basename(msoa_files))

# read all shapefiles and joined into 1 sf object
msoa <- map_dfr(msoa_files, ~ st_read(.x, quiet = TRUE)) %>%
  st_transform(27700)

msoa

ksi_msoa_join <- st_join(
  tfl_ksi, 
  msoa, 
  join = st_within
)

```
#Count KSI per MSOA and join back to MSOA map
```{r}
# Count KSI per MSOA and join back to MSOA map
msoa_ksi <- ksi_msoa_join %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  count(msoa21cd, name = "ksi_n")

msoa_map <- msoa %>%
  left_join(msoa_ksi, by = "msoa21cd") %>%
  mutate(ksi_n = ifelse(is.na(ksi_n), 0, ksi_n))

```

#Choroplet MSOA map
```{r}
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(msoa_map) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = ksi_n), color = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = london, fill = NA, linewidth = 0.3) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "C", name = "KSI count") +
  labs(
    title = "Killed or Seriously Injured (KSI) casualties by MSOA (2024)",
    subtitle = "Counts aggregated from TfL casualty data; MSOA 2021 boundaries",
    caption = "Source: TfL casualty data (2024) + ONS MSOA 2021 boundaries"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

```
#MSOA adjacency
```{r}
library(spdep)

msoa_nb <- poly2nb(msoa_map)
msoa_w  <- nb2listw(msoa_nb, style = "W", zero.policy = TRUE)

```

#GlobalMoran's I
```{r}
global_moran <- moran.test(
  msoa_map$ksi_n,
  msoa_w,
  zero.policy = TRUE
)

global_moran

```
#Local Moran (LISA)
```{r}
lisa <- localmoran(
  msoa_map$ksi_n,
  msoa_w,
  zero.policy = TRUE
)

msoa_map$lisa_I <- lisa[,1]
msoa_map$lisa_p <- lisa[,5]

```

#Cluster clarification
```{r}
mean_ksi <- mean(msoa_map$ksi_n, na.rm = TRUE)

msoa_map <- msoa_map %>%
  mutate(
    cluster = case_when(
      ksi_n >= mean_ksi & lisa_I > 0 & lisa_p <= 0.05 ~ "High-High",
      ksi_n <  mean_ksi & lisa_I > 0 & lisa_p <= 0.05 ~ "Low-Low",
      TRUE ~ "Not significant"
    )
  )

```

#LISA map
```{r}
ggplot(msoa_map) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cluster), color = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = london, fill = NA, linewidth = 0.3) +
  scale_fill_manual(
    values = c(
      "High-High" = "red",
      "Low-Low" = "blue",
      "Not significant" = "grey80"
    )
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Local Moran’s I (LISA) Clusters of KSI Accidents (2024)",
    subtitle = "MSOA-level spatial clustering based on KSI counts",
    caption = "Source: TfL casualty data (2024); MSOA boundaries (2021)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

```





####Analysis result:

#KSI points map:
The map suggests a higher concentration of KSI accidents in central London and along major transport corridors. While this visual pattern indicates potential spatial clustering, formal spatial statistical tests are required to determine whether these patterns are statistically significant.

#KSI distribution map:
The choropleth map shows where Killed or Seriously Injured (KSI) victims were located in Greater London in 2024, grouped by MSOA level.  There is clear geographical heterogeneity, which means that KSI occurrences are not spread out evenly across space.

 Central London MSOAs had more KSI casualties than other locations, especially in the center city where there are a lot of roads and a lot of people using them.  These MSOAs have a lot more KSI than regions in outer London, which usually have a lot less KSI.  This trend shows that there is a strong link between the number of accidents and how busy a city is, such as how many cars are on the road, how complicated the roads are, and how many different types of land are used.

 On the other hand, many outlying MSOAs have continuously low KSI counts, which means that there are less people on the roads and less interaction between different types of road users.  The slow drop in KSI counts from central London to outer London shows a strong spatial gradient instead than random variation.

 Overall, the map gives early visual proof that KSI incidences are clustered in space, which supports the idea that significant traffic deaths in London are clustered in space.  This visual pattern supports the use of spatial autocorrelation approaches like Global Moran's I and Local Indicators of Spatial Association (LISA) to formally evaluate and find statistically significant clusters.

#LISA map 
The Local Moran's I (LISA) analysis shows that the Killed or Seriously Injured (KSI) deaths in London MSOAs in 2024 are not random.

 The LISA cluster map shows a definite High–High cluster in central London. This means that MSOAs with high KSI counts are surrounded by other MSOAs with high KSI counts.  This pattern indicates statistically significant regional clustering of severe road traffic injuries, as opposed to a random distribution.

 On the other hand, most MSOAs in outer London are not significant, which means that their KSI counts do not exhibit a statistically significant geographical relationship with other locations.  Notably, there are no noticeable Low–Low clusters, which means that there are few or no regions in 2024 where areas with continuously low KSI counts are packed together.

 The High–High clusters are probably linked to places with a lot of transportation activity, like downtown London, where there are a lot of roads, a lot of traffic, and complicated urban surroundings.  These results back up the idea that KSI accidents happen in groups in certain areas, and also point out certain MSOAs that may need specific road safety measures as part of TfL's Vision Zero approach.

 Overall, the LISA results add to the Global Moran's I results by showing exactly where localized KSI hotspots are. This gives policymakers and planners important spatial information to help them decide what to do first.

#Conclusion:
The analysis demonstrates that Killed or Seriously Injured (KSI) accidents in London in 2024 display considerable regional clustering at the MSOA level, rather than a random distribution.  Global Moran's I shows that there is overall positive spatial autocorrelation, which means that MSOAs with similar KSI counts are likely to be close together.

 The Local Moran's I (LISA) analysis reveals that the most significant KSI clusters are High–High clusters located in central London.  These MSOAs have a lot of KSI deaths, and they are next to other MSOAs that also have a lot of KSI deaths.  This pattern of space shows that central London will be a major hotspot for significant road traffic injuries in 2024.

 On the other hand, most outer London MSOAs do not show statistically significant clustering. This means that KSI incidents are more spread out or isolated in these locations.  Overall, the results show that KSI incidents in London in 2024 are grouped in space, with the most important concentrations happening in central urban MSOAs.


